obo:ECO_0007719  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_5354  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: ORP2 knockdown causes a decrease of Ca2+ influx signals in a cholesterol-dependent manner.\n\n\"Initially, we examined the general presynaptic localization (VGlut1) of the voltage-gated Ca2+ channel CaV2.1, which was found unchanged in ORP2 KD hippocampal neurons (Figure 5A). Next, we investigated presynaptic Ca2+ influx by fluorescence live cell imaging of SynGCamp6f, a fast Ca2+ sensor fused to synaptophysin and thus located to SVs.46 Compared to control conditions, Ca2+ influx signals were reduced in ORP2 KD hippocampal neurons (Figures 5B and 5C).\n\nThe relative reduction of Ca2+ influx in ORP2 KD hippocampal neurons was especially apparent at stimulations with single (64.9% reduction; 0.35 ± 0.07 sc vs. 0.12 ± 0.03 ORP2 KD) or double (49.9% reduction; 0.65 ± 0.09 sc vs. 0.32 ± 0.05 ORP2 KD) APs (Figure 5B, 1 AP and 2 AP). Of note, the decrease in Ca2+ influx was more profound than what could be expected from the roughly 16% reduction of SVs assessed by electron microscopy (Figure 2H). This particularly visible impact of ORP2 KD at single and double APs indicates impaired Ca2+ channel activation and/or function.\". Experimental description: M&M: \"Experimental models: Organisms/strains - Mouse: C57/BL6N (WT)\"\n\nshRNA knockdown;\nf(U6)snrw-ORP2 shRNA-1, Weber-Boyvat et al., (21) (PMID:32734583)" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2023-03-13" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5354" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

